# Spark Companion Memory & Context™ (Spec 112)

**Full document:** `docs/SPARK_COMPANION_MEMORY_CONTEXT_FRAMEWORK.md`

**OS layer:** [008 Business Memory Engine](../spark-intelligence-foundation/08-memory-engine.md) · [007 Context Strategy](../spark-intelligence-foundation/007-context-strategy.md) · **[Spec 117 Business Brain Memory & Retrieval](../docs/SPARK_BUSINESS_BRAIN_MEMORY_RETRIEVAL_FRAMEWORK.md)** · **Tone:** [Spec 111 Hospitality](../docs/SPARK_HOSPITALITY_FRAMEWORK.md)

## Vision

Members think: *"I'm glad I didn't have to explain that again."*

Never: *"How did Spark know that?"*

**Trust > personalization.**

## Four memory types

1. **Business Memory™** — long-term facts
2. **Project Memory™** — until complete/archived/deleted
3. **Relationship Memory™** — communication style (not surveillance)
4. **Session Memory™** — expires unless member saves

## Philosophy question (before every persist)

> Will remembering this genuinely make the member's life easier in the future?

No → don't remember.

## Never assume

Temporary ("I'm overwhelmed today") ≠ permanent memory. Ask permission.

Observation ≠ memory. Repeated patterns → still ask before suggesting.

## Context priority

Current conversation → current project → Business Assets → long-term memory

## Permission required for permanent storage

"I can remember that if you'd like." · "Should I remember this for future conversations?"

## Never remember

Moods, arguments, health/politics/religion/family (unless requested), embarrassing surprises

## Memory Center™

Sections: Business · Projects · Preferences · Accessibility · Conversation Style · Environment · Saved Decisions

Member controls: edit · delete · add · turn off

## Hospitality language

"I thought this might save us a little time." not "I remembered this."

"Last time we decided..." not "You always..."

## Trust tests (internal, before remember)

Reduce effort? · Expected? · Would surprise? · Forgetting frustrates? · Permission builds trust?

